I recently opened up a new shop & studio on Main Street in the little town of Coudersport, PA that has the most amazing windows! ♥️ When my Woodland Keeper rolls arrived in the middle of my move into this new space, I knew immediately that I had to create my holiday window displays using this collection! 🍄 I separated the sixteen prints into two groups — this pink, coral, orange & berry palette for one window that inspired a snowy, magical, holiday meadow with my giant anthro dupe mushrooms and a pile of patchwork, wholecloth & velvet pillows!

A closeup look at my Magical Winter Meadow window at my new shop & studio in a Coudersport PA ✨🌿❄️🍄 — featuring handpainted motifs from & quilted projects made with my Woodland Keeper fabric collection for @artgalleryfabrics + giant painted cardboard & quilted fabric mushrooms that I made from the boxes my fabric rolls arrived in that were inspired by @anthropologie @anthrowindows #anthrodisplay artist @blair.stitch.project.ny! Made with Cleo’s help, of course! 🤍 Opening a space right on Main St felt scary, but has always been such a big dream of mine, especially to have this opportunity to do and share so many of the things I love all in one place — my art & handmade items made with fabrics I design, my passion for visual merchandising, and soon a place to welcome fellow creatives and folks who want to learn! ❤️

This all makes me wish I had known how to sew well sooner, so I could have made things like this for my own children, that I’m sure would have become heirlooms in our family. 

How about you, were you sewing early enough in your life to make things for your own dolls or your children’s dolls? Did you keep those things? I’d love to read any stories you can share! 🧡

Wendy Chow’s @the.weekendquilter beautiful new book, the #QuiltedHomeHandbook, arrived at my door yesterday! With the snowstorm picking up, nowhere to be, the fireplace on, and fresh cup of coffee, everything had aligned so I could take my time taking in this stunning book. It was glorious, and my gosh is this a good book!! 

The Quilted Home Handbook is truly a handbook packed full of helpful instructions perfect for beginners and experienced quilters alike. It features 15+ absolutely beautiful quilt projects, and Wendy’s illustrations and stunning photos for each project are all so special. You can tell she poured her heart & soul into this book, and I can’t wait for everyone to see it! 🧡

I’ve settled on making her #brickbybrickcushion first in prints from Gloria + Woodland Keeper, and of course I’ll be sure to share once it’s finished! If you’d like to order a copy you can grab a signed ✍🏽 copy from Wendy’s online store by visiting @the.weekendquilter or purchase it from your fave book retailer! ❤️

So many have been messaging me to make a shareable post, so they can help spread the word, and I’m so grateful! 

If you didn’t see my stories here + on my FB page the @hotelcrittenden, a historical building in our little town Coudersport, PA suffered a devasting fire this past Wednesday. Within this building is a restaurant/bar, hotel rooms + apartments, the Riley Gallery, and my new shop & studio. 

The damage from the fire is extensive, and although fire & smoke did not reach down into my space, when I was finally able to go in with firefighters water was pouring down through every ceiling fixture. Thankfully, with the help of so many amazing firefighters & shop neighbors, we were able to empty my full studio including all of my fabrics & machines + the majority of my shop merchandise to a nearby shop safely, and with minimal damage. It’s a miracle, honestly! 

I’m heartbroken to no longer have this space. It was something truly special, and I was really, really proud of it. For all of you asking how to help, my main concern right now is for the hotel manager, Chandra. After lowering people down first from the 3rd floor safely, Chandra then had to jump by herself and suffered multiple compound fractures and broken bones in her lower leg & foot. She was rushed to a trauma center, had surgery, will need more, and has a very long road of healing ahead her. 

For those able to help my incredible friend Chandra❤️ there’s been a GoFundme set up here — https://gofund.me/bbd17156
A bright spot in all this mess, Cleo is loving this new dining room fabric shelf ❤️

The blessing, and sometimes the burden, of building my new shop these past several months is how all-consuming it all became immediately. After years of working from home, followed by five years working from a closed studio space, moving into my new space was an exciting, essential change. The goal was to create a beautiful space that would be inspiring, where I truly loved to be, and to share that with whoever came through the door. So far, so good. The day before the fire had been a truly perfect, sunny, shop day. After a long, dreary winter the cheerful atmosphere and mood of the day was palpable. It was simple, special, and sacred. 

Immediately following the fire, the race to save all of my shop belogings preceded days of sorting through all of it left in two massive heaps in the back of a neighboring shop, fully aware of how much worse it all could have been while feeling a mix of overwhelming concern for those most affected, immense gratitude for so many who showed up to help me, exhausted and heartbroken.

By Friday everything was nearly settled. The owner of the local shop that came to my rescue, Mama Made, invited me to add my merchandise to her lovely shop as a vendor, and everything else is either in storage or in our dining room where I'll be working until the dream each of us was building can be put back together. 

Each day since September the new shop & studio had been at the forefront of my decisions and schedule, so I'm honestly feeling a little lost today. I know I need a little time still to process and find my new routine, but since making has always been my antidote for when life gets stressful, I've decided to start with something both familiar & comforting, these happy ninepatch blocks. ❤️

This morning I noticed there’s a theme running through all that I’ve made since I lost my studio & shop, of comfort and healing. Ten days after the fire I finally felt settled enough to sit down at my machine to sew again. I was lost, but knew I could find my next move if I just stayed creative. I started making simple, tiny ninepatch blocks, which for me equals pattern therapy, it’s healing work. I have two new fabric collections I’m both excited to use & behind on promoting — Daisy (meaning: a new beginning, joy & cheerfulness) + my Storyteller Plaids (representing: comfort), all I’m in need of. After a few days, and the blur of making nearly a hundred ninepatch blocks, I could feel the task absorb my grief, myself move past the shock of losing so much so fast, and able to start setting goals. What I know for certain is whether or not I’m able to rebuild the space I just lost, a new space opens up, I continue vending, or reopen online, that if I fill my days staying creative, inspired, productive, accomplished, then I’ll remain positive. And because creating handmade products with the fabrics I design brings me so much joy, my healing stack of ninepatch blocks became a new batch of Quilt Covered Notebooks. The design inspired by colorful, vintage picnic quilts and what I imagine to be the perfect garden journal or sketchbook. 🌼🪴📓✏️ 

These Quilt Covered Notebooks will be in my online shop soon, DM’s are welcomed to pre-order, and I plan to share next a batch of new handmade items I finished yesterday continuing with the theme of comfort & healing. ❤️

#afgdaisy #agfstorytellerplaids #quiltednotebookcover #ninepatch

Several weeks ago I made myself an aromatherapy weighted eye pillow filled with lavender buds & essential oil + rice. As soon as I snipped the last closing stitch threads, I heated it up to try. I placed the cozy flannel side over my eyes & forehead, the lovely scent brought immediate relaxation, and I could feel the light weighted pressure ease my tension. I knew I absolutely had to make more! 

I mentioned in my last post that I had noticed the theme of comfort & healing in my creativity since I’ve gotten back to making after the fire. How perfect that I had all the materials needed to make these waiting for me for when I could find the time. More healing work 🧡 

I’m planning an online shop update for May 2, and I’ll have these + many more handmade goodies available. I’m so grateful for the encouragement & support so many of you have showed me as I get through this. Thank you! ❤️

A big THANK YOU to all who’ve given love for the reveal of my next collection with @artgalleryfabrics, The Flower Fields. Shown here is my Blooming Burst floral print in the Sunrise colorway ♥️ The Flower Fieds & Flower Seeds collections are available for shops to PRE order now, and will ship in January, so soon! 

This collection celebrates the universal love for all things floral, showcasing their elegance, vibrancy, and remarkable RESILIENCY — a word I plan to carry with me into the new year after living through the most difficult year of my life. I don’t share very often about my hardships and personal struggles, always trying to keep things moving, positive & pretty to look at. But today it feels important for me to acknowledge the deep personal significance this collection has for me that might not be apparent to others. Having the opportunity to design fabric that’s made into so many beautiful, incredible things brings so much joy to my life, it’s healing and I’m grateful beyond words for all of it + YOU! ♥️

Isn’t she pretty?! 😍 I have so many project ideas for this print from simple zip pouches to a quilt made alternating these floral squares with nine patch blocks to cutting binding from the outer border design — I can’t wait!!

Have you ever sat at your machine, with a basket of scraps, cutting mat & ruler nearby, and you just start cutting and piecing with no plan? After finishing up my last batch of Maven Zip Bags I was left with a pile of narrow strips and little scraps that were too pretty not to turn into something. Well, without any plan I ended up with this first + + + quilt block. Seeing it now I realize how perfectly fitting it is to the recent conversations I’ve been having with friends about setting positive goals & intentions as the new year approaches. This past week I’ve been setting mine early, as I feel like I’m finally on the other side of a very difficult season in my life. In years past I’ve found and held onto a word or short phrase that reflects the positive changes I want to work towards, and this year I think I’ve found a quilt block. ♥️

I love to make reusable gift bags for the holidays, so I thought I’d share a couple options for those of you planning to make some, too!  Both patterns are easy & quick makes that create the cutest drawstring bags! 

The first one is made by @artgalleryfabrics in my Cozy & Magical Gift of Giving print using the tutorial by @quiltsocial — https://quiltsocial.com/fabric-gift-bags/

The second batch are made by 💁🏻‍♀️ in more of my Cozy & Magical + Storyteller Plaids prints using the Easy Drawstring Bag tutorial by @purlsoho — https://www.purlsoho.com/create/2019/12/09/easy-drawstring-bags-in-spectrum-cotton/

I hope these options are just what you’ve been looking for! ♥️

This time of year, few things make me as happy as seeing so many posts from those of you who are currently sewing with or are sharing something you’ve created using the holiday collections I’ve designed for @artgalleryfabrics! It’s truly amazing!! ✨🎅🏼🎄♥️🎄🎁✨

Here’s my own stash of Cozy & Joyful, Cozy & Magical, and my first holiday Plaids that I’m sewing with this week, too!

It was nearly impossible to fit all twenty-four rolls into one shot 🪜💁🏻‍♀️ — Yes! The Flower Fields include sixteen brand new amazing florals & are accompanied by The Flower Seeds, a collection of eight new blenders that coordinate perfectly! ❤️

The Flower Fields and The Flower Seeds are available for shops to preorder now from @artgalleryfabrics and are scheduled to begin arriving to shops later this month! I can’t wait!!
